snippet: After $6 billion, two dozen presidential primary days, four general election debates and more TV ads than anyone could watch, the two parties essentially fought to a standstill.
abstract: News analysis; activity leading up to presidential election has done little to change political balance in Washington, which closely resembles the Congressional party affiliations that existed during Pres Obama's first four years in office; with elections concluded, margins in the House and Senate each changed by only two or three seats.
lead_paragraph: After $6 billion, two dozen presidential primary days, four general election debates and more TV ads than anyone could watch, the two parties essentially fought to a standstill.

headline.seo: Votes Does Little to Change Standoff in Washington
headline.main: Obama Wins a Clear Victory, but Balance of Power Is Unchanged in Washington
headline.print_headline: Smoke Clears to Show a Battlefield Little Changed
headline.sub: Debate Over Size of Federal Government Left Unresolved
